00:21:05,864 --> 00:21:10,597
was hidden 50 pounds
of C-4 plastic explosive.

240
00:21:10,669 --> 00:21:14,469
When it was detonated, it disintegrated
the street side of the building...

241
00:21:14,539 --> 00:21:18,134
obliterating dozens
of government offices...

242
00:21:18,210 --> 00:21:20,735
the building's day care <i>center....</i>

243
00:21:21,647 --> 00:21:24,912
and the St. Louis branch
of the Internal Revenue Service...

244
00:21:24,983 --> 00:21:28,384
which was ultimately determined
to be the target of the attack.

245
00:21:28,453 --> 00:21:33,152
The truck was leased by
this 33-year-old electrician...

246
00:21:34,593 --> 00:21:36,083
Dean Scobee.

247
00:21:36,862 --> 00:21:40,923
Scobee had served some prison time
for tax evasion...

248
00:21:40,999 --> 00:21:45,060
and surveillance videos showed
that he was inside the vehicle...

249
00:21:45,137 --> 00:21:47,469
leaving him among the 63 dead.

250
00:21:47,539 --> 00:21:50,099
Does anyone not remember this?

251
00:21:51,877 --> 00:21:53,902
You all remember the results
of the investigation?

252
00:21:53,979 --> 00:21:57,779
- They said Scobee acted alone.
- One man, no conspirators.

253
00:21:58,850 --> 00:22:00,647
Right?

254
00:22:01,453 --> 00:22:05,549
He cheated the IRS. They caught
him at it, so he blew 'em up.

255
00:22:08,226 --> 00:22:12,458
This is a guy who people
described as average.

256
00:22:12,531 --> 00:22:13,964
Friendly.

257
00:22:15,300 --> 00:22:18,531
He'd been in the army,
but as a radio man.

258
00:22:18,603 --> 00:22:21,299
He had very little experience
with munitions.

259
00:22:21,373 --> 00:22:25,503
His parents considered him
a moderate conservative.

260
00:22:25,577 --> 00:22:31,311
Two weeks prior to this, he received
a pay raise at his electrician's job.

261
00:22:31,383 --> 00:22:35,319
Does that sound like a man who's
on the edge or a man who needed a push?

262
00:22:35,387 --> 00:22:37,184
Huh?

263
00:22:37,255 --> 00:22:39,621
Come on. I don't know.
I'm just asking.

264
00:22:39,691 --> 00:22:43,627
Come on, Professor.
The Feds did this huge investigation.

265
00:22:43,695 --> 00:22:45,993
That's right,
an investigation, I forgot.

266
00:22:46,064 --> 00:22:48,191
Well...

267
00:22:48,266 --> 00:22:51,201
the investigation
didn't satisfy me.

268
00:22:53,171 --> 00:22:55,799
Miss O'Neill,
when you first heard the news...

269
00:22:55,874 --> 00:22:59,833
terrorist attack in your own country...
how did that make you feel?

270
00:22:59,911 --> 00:23:01,503
- Come on.
- Well...

271
00:23:02,581 --> 00:23:05,607
What did you feel?

272
00:23:05,684 --> 00:23:07,117
Angry.

273
00:23:08,186 --> 00:23:10,245
Scared and stressed.

274
00:23:10,322 --> 00:23:12,882
- Did you feel safe?
- No.

275
00:23:13,959 --> 00:23:18,328
And then the next day,
when they found Scobee dead...

276
00:23:18,397 --> 00:23:20,592
did you feel some relief?

277
00:23:20,665 --> 00:23:22,599
Did safety return?

278
00:23:35,313 --> 00:23:38,009
The people in that building,
they felt safe...

279
00:23:39,651 --> 00:23:44,384
secure, just like you feel now.

280
00:23:46,825 --> 00:23:49,623
And then an instant later...

281
00:23:51,563 --> 00:23:53,497
In an instant...

282
00:23:56,668 --> 00:23:59,603
they were gone forever.

283
00:24:06,645 --> 00:24:10,172
We needed to have
this man to blame.

284
00:24:14,152 --> 00:24:16,382
We don't want others.

285
00:24:16,455 --> 00:24:18,650
We want one name...

286
00:24:18,723 --> 00:24:20,816
and we want it fast...

287
00:24:20,892 --> 00:24:24,658
because it gives us
our security back.

288
00:24:27,632 --> 00:24:30,362
We can say,
"Here was the one man...

289
00:24:30,435 --> 00:24:32,528
unlike the rest of us.

290
00:24:33,839 --> 00:24:37,468
We named him,
and he's no more.

291
00:24:37,542 --> 00:24:40,170
And his reasons,
they're gone too."

292
00:24:40,245 --> 00:24:43,271
But the truth is,
we don't know his reasons.

293
00:24:43,348 --> 00:24:46,112
We don't know why Scobee did it,
why it came to this.

294
00:24:46,184 --> 00:24:49,119
We can pretend we do...
the ten grand in taxes...

295
00:24:49,187 --> 00:24:51,121
but we don't <i>know....</i>

296
00:24:52,190 --> 00:24:54,124
and we'll never know.

297
00:24:57,128 --> 00:25:01,030
And still, we feel safe...

298
00:25:04,736 --> 00:25:07,204
because we know his name.

299
00:25:08,607 --> 00:25:11,701
As God is my witness...

300
00:25:11,776 --> 00:25:14,438
I promise to give...

301
00:25:14,513 --> 00:25:16,447
friendship to those in need.

302
00:25:18,617 --> 00:25:20,608
Help to those in trouble.

303
00:25:22,354 --> 00:25:25,118
I will work with faith and honor...

304
00:25:27,125 --> 00:25:29,355
to uphold the Discoverer code.

305
00:25:32,097 --> 00:25:34,395
To respect <i>myself....</i>

306
00:25:35,267 --> 00:25:37,201
my family...

307
00:25:37,269 --> 00:25:39,203
and my country.

308
00:25:40,305 --> 00:25:43,832
Ladies and gentlemen, please welcome
Junior Discovery Troop 474.

309
00:25:59,424 --> 00:26:01,517
<i>This is Oliver's study...</i>

310
00:26:01,593 --> 00:26:03,823
where he, you know,
gets away from the kids...

311
00:26:03,895 --> 00:26:05,829
and me, I suppose.

312
00:26:07,432 --> 00:26:10,162
These are all projects
you've worked on?

313
00:26:10,235 --> 00:26:12,567
I wish.
No, I collect sketches...

314
00:26:12,637 --> 00:26:15,197
blueprints,
designs of old buildings.

315
00:26:15,273 --> 00:26:17,503
This is a front view of Monticello.

316
00:26:17,576 --> 00:26:20,010
- Down there is the Woolworth Building.
- It's his hobby.

317
00:26:20,078 --> 00:26:23,070
- The St. Louis Arch.
- Yes, correct.

318
00:26:23,848 --> 00:26:26,840
So, then all of these drawings,
these buildings...

319
00:26:26,918 --> 00:26:28,852
they're not just
for your job, then?

320
00:26:30,455 --> 00:26:32,582
Oh. So they're not
all shopping malls.

321
00:26:32,657 --> 00:26:36,991
No, I don't know of any architecturally
significant shopping malls.

322
00:26:37,062 --> 00:26:40,031
Oh, honey, you just
haven't built them yet.

323
00:26:43,234 --> 00:26:45,202
- Who's hungry?
- I'm famished.

324
00:26:45,270 --> 00:26:49,639
Come on. I've got some
really delicious puff pastry.

325
00:26:52,377 --> 00:26:54,470
They've got to work so hard
when they're there.

326
00:26:54,546 --> 00:26:57,071
You've gotta keep 'em
in the seats.

327
00:26:57,148 --> 00:26:58,581
You know?

328
00:26:59,784 --> 00:27:02,685
Politically, there's something
to be said for that.

329
00:27:02,754 --> 00:27:05,052
Yeah, it was a lot of fun.
Here we are leaving the church.

330
00:27:05,123 --> 00:27:07,182
Everyone thought we were
going to Mexico.

331
00:27:07,258 --> 00:27:09,226
- Where were you going?
- We were <i>going there....</i>

332
00:27:09,294 --> 00:27:11,854
but the plane
never left the ground.

333
00:27:11,930 --> 00:27:13,591
Some kind of engine trouble.

334
00:27:13,665 --> 00:27:18,602
Couldn't leave till morning, so we spent
the night at the Wichita Airport Motel.

335
00:27:18,670 --> 00:27:20,831
How romantic!

336
00:27:20,905 --> 00:27:24,466
- Well, for $19, it was wonderful.
- How long you two been married?

337
00:27:25,577 --> 00:27:29,240
- Well, 12 years in August.
- What kind of example is that?

338
00:27:30,315 --> 00:27:35,617
Well, I don't think we learn
responsibility from politicians.

339
00:27:35,687 --> 00:27:37,780
We really learn it from family.

340
00:27:37,856 --> 00:27:40,120
It's the people that we care about.

341
00:27:40,191 --> 00:27:43,820
- It's what they care about.
- He died when I was a teenager.

342
00:27:44,796 --> 00:27:46,593
Oh, I'm sorry.

343
00:27:46,665 --> 00:27:48,098
Farm accident.

344
00:27:50,335 --> 00:27:52,963
- Where would you say you get yours from?
- My what? My values?

345
00:27:58,343 --> 00:28:01,039
- Probably from my wife.
- Values?

346
00:28:02,113 --> 00:28:04,138
What values?

347
00:28:04,215 --> 00:28:07,116
Michael and I were talking about
where you get your values <i>from....</i>

348
00:28:07,185 --> 00:28:09,915
and we were both saying
it's mostly from family.

349
00:28:09,988 --> 00:28:13,685
Well, where else you gonna get 'em?
Celebrities? Politicians?

350
00:28:13,758 --> 00:28:15,692
Not in this century.

351
00:28:17,962 --> 00:28:19,987
I just think it's...

352
00:28:20,065 --> 00:28:24,399
a sorry state of affairs when you can't
find a role model to cast your vote for.

353
00:28:24,469 --> 00:28:26,903
It's not even role models,
necessarily.

354
00:28:26,971 --> 00:28:31,840
It's just people who acknowledge
the consequences of their actions.

355
00:28:31,910 --> 00:28:36,779
Or pay for those actions. I think we
should put some politicians in jail.

356
00:28:38,316 --> 00:28:41,376
You can't ask government
to be infallible.

357
00:28:41,453 --> 00:28:44,081
You just can't.
But you can ask it to be accountable.

358
00:28:46,858 --> 00:28:49,190
I can ask it to be honest.

359
00:28:49,260 --> 00:28:51,922
You know, when Leah died...

360
00:28:51,996 --> 00:28:55,193
all I wanted was someone...

361
00:28:55,266 --> 00:28:59,066
to tell me,
"W e made a mistake."

362
00:28:59,137 --> 00:29:02,629
You know?
"We made a mistake.

363
00:29:02,707 --> 00:29:04,902
Your wife suffered for it...

364
00:29:05,977 --> 00:29:08,411
and we'd take it back
a hundred times if we could."

365
00:29:09,247 --> 00:29:11,442
But, uh...

366
00:29:11,516 --> 00:29:13,916
they don't say that.

367
00:29:13,985 --> 00:29:15,418
She would've.

368
00:29:21,526 --> 00:29:24,290
Some of them knew her.

369
00:29:29,067 --> 00:29:32,594
They work so hard at being able
to look you in the eye.

370
00:29:51,890 --> 00:29:53,255
Excuse me.

371
00:30:07,105 --> 00:30:09,198
Leave him alone.
He's fine.

372
00:30:13,411 --> 00:30:14,844
Sorry.

373
00:30:22,987 --> 00:30:25,820
- I see how much you miss her.
- There are just these times...

374
00:30:25,890 --> 00:30:29,792
when you realize how much
your own life is out of your hands.

375
00:30:33,231 --> 00:30:35,324
What are you gonna do?

376
00:30:39,270 --> 00:30:41,363
I guess you can have faith.

377
00:30:44,175 --> 00:30:47,542
Try to make a difference
while you can with Grant...

378
00:30:49,347 --> 00:30:51,281
to your classes.

379
00:30:55,887 --> 00:30:57,821
What about you?

380
00:31:00,725 --> 00:31:02,659
Got my family...

381
00:31:04,696 --> 00:31:06,891
and the buildings I leave behind.

382
00:31:11,603 --> 00:31:13,537
That's it.

383
00:31:13,605 --> 00:31:15,937
Get your shoulder up
a little bit, okay?

384
00:31:16,007 --> 00:31:18,805
Step into it. Watch that ball
until it hits the bat.

385
00:31:18,877 --> 00:31:20,811
That's it!

386
00:31:22,914 --> 00:31:25,007
You want some Crackerjack?

387
00:31:29,254 --> 00:31:33,748
You sure? Popcorn and caramel.
It builds your muscles.

388
00:31:33,825 --> 00:31:35,190
All right.

389
00:31:37,061 --> 00:31:38,995
Hey, atta way, Faraday.

390
00:31:40,298 --> 00:31:44,496
- He's gettin' some confidence.
- He's a strong kid.

391
00:31:46,437 --> 00:31:49,804
- He's been dealt some hard breaks.
- Atta way to swing.

392
00:31:51,476 --> 00:31:55,071
- You give him strength.
- I'm tryin'.

393
00:31:55,146 --> 00:31:57,341
You do.

394
00:31:57,415 --> 00:32:00,213
Gettin' on with your life.
That's important for him to see.

395
00:32:02,854 --> 00:32:05,118
He just wishes someone had to pay.

396
00:32:06,224 --> 00:32:07,350
What?

397
00:32:08,726 --> 00:32:12,628
For his mother.
He wishes someone had to pay.

398
00:32:12,697 --> 00:32:14,790
He's talked to you about her?

399
00:32:16,200 --> 00:32:18,600
Our people send her in with
the wrong information then say...

400
00:32:18,670 --> 00:32:20,604
"Hey, not my fault."

401
00:32:22,941 --> 00:32:25,102
I can't live with that...

402
00:32:25,176 --> 00:32:28,373
for you,
let alone a nine-year-old boy.

403
00:32:29,814 --> 00:32:32,442
Grant talked to you
about his mother?

404
00:32:34,552 --> 00:32:36,144
Well, yeah.

405
00:32:36,220 --> 00:32:39,621
I hope that's all right.
We talk about a lot of things.

406
00:32:41,259 --> 00:32:43,284
He's a smart kid.

407
00:32:46,364 --> 00:32:48,889
Way to go, Grant.

408
00:32:50,868 --> 00:32:53,462
We're never more wise
than when we're children.

409
00:32:53,538 --> 00:32:55,472
They say it, and it's true.

410
00:32:57,241 --> 00:32:59,709
We'll never see things
that clear again.

411
00:33:05,483 --> 00:33:07,576
Let me have a hit.

412
00:33:19,630 --> 00:33:22,565
Come on, now, it's dinnertime.
Wash your hands.

413
00:33:22,633 --> 00:33:25,864
- I'm eating with Brady.
- No, come on, now.

414
00:33:26,804 --> 00:33:29,466
Michael, I'm sorry.
Brady invited him over for dinner.

415
00:33:29,540 --> 00:33:33,032
- I thought he'd asked you.
- Can I eat with Brady, Dad?

416
00:33:37,749 --> 00:33:41,207
Okay, if his dad
says it's all right.

417
00:33:41,285 --> 00:33:43,378
Is it all right, kids?

418
00:33:46,791 --> 00:33:49,282
I can fly!

419
00:34:06,377 --> 00:34:08,072
- <i>Good afternoon, U Penn.</i>
- Transcript office, please.

420
00:34:10,048 --> 00:34:13,540
- <i>Transcripts.</i>
- I'm calling from Washington University.

421
00:34:13,618 --> 00:34:17,452
We have a student who's applying for
graduate work in our history department.

422
00:34:17,522 --> 00:34:20,821
I need to verify his
undergrad record with you guys.

423
00:34:21,893 --> 00:34:24,987
He's been out of school
for some time.

424
00:34:26,831 --> 00:34:28,765
The name's Oliver Lang.

425
00:34:29,934 --> 00:34:32,368
Are you telling me that you
took this out of his mailbox?

426
00:34:32,437 --> 00:34:34,962
- That is illegal.
- Tell me if you think this is strange.

427
00:34:35,039 --> 00:34:37,701
The University of Pennsylvania
keeps sending him alumni stuff...

428
00:34:37,775 --> 00:34:39,709
for a 20-year reunion.

429
00:34:39,777 --> 00:34:43,304
He says he went to Kansas State. They
have him mixed up with someone else.

430
00:34:43,381 --> 00:34:46,475
So I call Penn.
I get that guy's transcripts.

431
00:34:46,551 --> 00:34:50,146
- What? Why? Michael! Oh, my God!
- Listen to me.

432
00:34:50,221 --> 00:34:53,588
That guy has a completely
different physical description.

433
00:34:53,658 --> 00:34:55,990
- He never took a class in engineering.
- Right...

434
00:34:56,060 --> 00:34:58,255
because they've got him mixed up
with somebody else.

435
00:34:58,329 --> 00:35:01,821
This U Penn Oliver
is the same age as Oliver.

436
00:35:01,899 --> 00:35:05,062
- Wait. As our Oliver?
- As our Oliver, yes.

437
00:35:05,136 --> 00:35:08,105
He graduated the same year, and...

438
00:35:08,172 --> 00:35:12,165
he comes from Carson, Kansas,
Oliver's hometown.

439
00:35:12,243 --> 00:35:15,508
Wait, I'm totally lost. You just said
that they're two different people.

440
00:35:15,580 --> 00:35:19,676
Yeah. Two people the same age
from the same small town!

441
00:35:19,750 --> 00:35:22,480
I looked it up.
It's a small town!

442
00:35:22,553 --> 00:35:24,851
Yeah, so what?

443
00:35:24,922 --> 00:35:27,482
Brooke, don't you think they would've
heard of each other, these guys?

444
00:35:27,558 --> 00:35:30,186
You know, growing up?
Gotten mixed up before?

445
00:35:30,261 --> 00:35:33,424
Oliver didn't say anything like that.
He just threw the letter away.

446
00:35:33,498 --> 00:35:35,432
- Well, wait a minute.
- So...

447
00:35:35,500 --> 00:35:38,162
There could be ten other Michael
Faradays in Northern Virginia.

448
00:35:38,236 --> 00:35:41,569
- You would never know that.
- So I called Kansas State.

449
00:35:41,639 --> 00:35:44,904
Here's what I'm saying.
Kansas State University...

450
00:35:44,976 --> 00:35:48,104
had no Oliver Lang on record,
from that year or any year.

451
00:35:48,179 --> 00:35:51,376
So either he didn't really
go to that school...

452
00:35:51,449 --> 00:35:54,009
or that's not his real name.

453
00:35:54,085 --> 00:35:57,816
Can I ask you something? Did you
do this to me when we started dating?

454
00:35:57,889 --> 00:35:59,880
- What?
- Call up my ex-boyfriends...

455
00:35:59,957 --> 00:36:01,925
and get my transcripts sent over?

456
00:36:01,993 --> 00:36:04,325
You've got to admit,
there's something not right here.

457
00:36:04,395 --> 00:36:07,956
No, this isn't right.
You have invaded his privacy.

458
00:36:08,032 --> 00:36:11,195
So maybe he lied about where
he went to college. Big deal.

459
00:36:11,269 --> 00:36:14,670
People lie about things all the time.
You don't have the right to spy on them.

460
00:36:14,739 --> 00:36:17,435
God, you of all people.

461
00:36:19,076 --> 00:36:21,169
Are you teaching the Bill of Rights
this semester...

462
00:36:21,245 --> 00:36:23,839
or did that not make the program?

463
00:36:26,450 --> 00:36:29,544
I don't know what you're doing.
We've made some friends here.

464
00:36:32,223 --> 00:36:33,656
All right?

465
00:36:35,593 --> 00:36:37,527
See you tonight.

466
00:36:58,015 --> 00:36:59,448
Lang.

467
00:37:41,425 --> 00:37:42,858
Shit.

468
00:37:58,976 --> 00:38:00,273
Fenimore.

469
00:38:02,313 --> 00:38:06,272
'Cause you've never been away from
home before. You're nine years old.

470
00:38:06,350 --> 00:38:08,443
Nine and a half.
There'll be grownups there.

471
00:38:08,519 --> 00:38:11,386
The answer is no, Grant.

472
00:38:11,455 --> 00:38:13,389
It's spring vacation.
You said I could go.

473
00:38:13,457 --> 00:38:16,517
Well, now I'm saying
that you can't go, Grant!

474
00:38:19,463 --> 00:38:23,058
Look, <i>maybe</i> you can go
for summer camp or something, okay?

475
00:38:23,134 --> 00:38:25,534
- Brady's going.
- Brady might not be the best kid...

476
00:38:25,603 --> 00:38:27,594
for you to be alone
in the woods with!

477
00:38:27,672 --> 00:38:31,164
- The answer is no!
- He's my best friend.

478
00:38:36,414 --> 00:38:41,909
Look, you want to go to camp, we'll go
to Aunt Ruth's and Uncle Rob's cabin.

479
00:38:41,986 --> 00:38:43,317
- Okay?
- That's a lie!

480
00:38:43,387 --> 00:38:47,881
- No it's not!
- You'll be too busy! You'll forget!

481
00:38:47,958 --> 00:38:50,620
- You and me, we'll go...
